5z9.title: Disjoint union of sets
5z9.clickbait: One of the most basic ways we have of joining two sets together.
5z9.text:
[summary: The *disjoint union* of two [3jz sets] is just the [5s8 union], but with the additional information that the two sets also don't have any elements in common. That is, we can use the phrase "disjoint union" to indicate that we've taken the union of two sets which have empty [5sb intersection]. The phrase can also be used to indicate a very slightly different operation: "do something to the elements of each set to make sure they don't overlap, and then take the union".]

[summary(Technical): The phrase "disjoint union" is used to mean one of two slightly different operations on [3jz sets]. It indicates either "just take the [5s8 union], but also notice that we've been careful to ensure that the sets have empty [5sb intersection]", or "perform a specific operation on each set to ensure that the resulting sets have empty intersection, and then take the union".]

[todo: summarise, noting that it's well-defined up to isomorphism]

# Definition of the disjoint union 

Let's look at $A = \{6,7\}$ and $B = \{6,8\}$.
These two sets overlap: they both contain $\{6\}$.

Even without quite knowing what "disjoint union" means, if the notion is to be well-defined up to isomorphism, then we require $A \sqcup B$ to have four elements: indeed, if we replace $A$ by the isomorphic $\{1,2\}$ and $B$ by the isomorphic $\{3,4\}$ (disjoint from $\{1,2\}$!), then the disjoint union can now be interpreted as just the usual union $\{1,2,3,4 \}$ which has four elements.

## Definition in terms of elements

"Disjoint union" can mean one of two things:

- The simple [5s8 union], together with the assertion that the two sets don't overlap;
- The operation "do something to the elements of each set to make sure they don't overlap, and then take the union".

In the case that the sets don't overlap, the second definition will always give us something isomorphic to the first definition. %%note: This is a fact about the specific construction we will use, so don't worry if it's not obvious yet.%%
In the case that the sets *do* overlap, the second definition is the only one that makes sense: the first definition doesn't really qualify for the word "definition" in that case.

What specifically do we do to the sets to make them disjoint? We'll now state the second definition exactly:

> The *disjoint union* of sets $A$ and $B$ is the set $A \sqcup B = A' \cup B'$, where $A' = \{ (a, 1): a \in A \}$ and $B' = \{(b, 2) : b \in B \}$. %%note: Recall that $(a,1)$ is the ordered pair whose first element is $a$ and whose second element is the number $1$.%%

That is, we tag each element of $A$ with "the fact that it comes from the first set", and we tag each element of $B$ with "the fact that it comes from the second set".

## Example

So to go into our specific example where $A = \{6,7\}$ and $B=\{6,8\}$, we have that $A' = \{ (6, 1), (7, 1) \}$ and $B' = \{ (6, 2), (8, 2) \}$, and the disjoint union is $$A \sqcup B = \{ (6,1), (7,1), (6,2), (8,2) \}$$
Notice that $A \cup B = \{ 6, 7, 8 \}$ has only three elements, because $6$ is in both $A$ and $B$ and that information has been lost on taking the union.
On the other hand, the disjoint union $A \sqcup B$ has the required four elements because we've retained the information that the two $6$'s are "different": they appear as $(6,1)$ and $(6,2)$ respectively.

## Exercise

What happens if $A = B = \{6,7\}$?

%%hidden(Show): Then $A' = \{(6,1), (7,1)\}$ and $B' = \{(6,2), (7,2)\}$, so $$A \sqcup B = \{(6,1),(7,1),(6,2),(7,2)\}$$
which again has four elements.%%
